#: ../../docs/classes/class_rigidbody.rst:16
msgid ""
"Physics Body whose position is determined through physics simulation in "
"3D space."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_rigidbody.rst:19
msgid "Description"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_rigidbody.rst:21
msgid ""
"This is the node that implements full 3D physics. This means that you do "
"not control a RigidBody directly. Instead, you can apply forces to it "
"(gravity, impulses, etc.), and the physics simulation will calculate the "
"resulting movement, collision, bouncing, rotating, etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_rigidbody.rst:23
msgid ""
"A RigidBody has 4 behavior :ref:`mode <class_RigidBody_property_mode>`\\ "
"s: Rigid, Static, Character, and Kinematic."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_rigidbody.rst:25
msgid ""
"**Note:** Don't change a RigidBody's position every frame or very often. "
"Sporadic changes work fine, but physics runs at a different granularity "
"(fixed Hz) than usual rendering (process callback) and maybe even in a "
"separate thread, so changing this from a process loop may result in "
"strange behavior. If you need to directly affect the body's state, use "
":ref:`_integrate_forces <class_RigidBody_method__integrate_forces>`, "
"which allows you to directly access the physics state."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_rigidbody.rst:27
msgid ""
"If you need to override the default physics behavior, you can write a "
"custom force integration function. See :ref:`custom_integrator "
"<class_RigidBody_property_custom_integrator>`."
msgstr ""

